<LENGTH>
<P>
1371 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN PASQUAL'S MEEK CONTINUES TO DRAW A CROWD; 
</P>
<P>
HIGH SCHOOLS: BUT WHETHER HE'S ENGULFED IN A SEA OF DEFENDERS OR A ROOMFUL OF 
RECRUITERS, THE 6-10 JUNIOR CENTER STANDS OUT. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVE McKIBBEN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ESCONDIDO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tom Buck, San Pasqual's basketball coach, points to the spot where Erik Meek 
stood that day, engulfed by five Escondido players. 
</P>
<P>
"They played a zone that had everyone in the lane, daring our other players to 
shoot the ball," Buck said. "The rest of our team went something like five for 
25, and we lost. But I think Erik still had 30 points." 
</P>
<P>
Escondido High Coach Mike Williams also vividly recalls the game two seasons 
ago, in Meek's freshman year. 
</P>
<P>
"We had Brooks Barnhard (now a freshman at University of San Diego) fronting 
him and another big guy behind him, and the other players were pretty close 
by," Williams said. "We were really successful playing him that way for two 
years. Once, we actually held him to 12 or 14 points. But that's because we got 
him into foul trouble." 
</P>
<P>
The attention surrounding Meek, a 6-foot-10, 220-pound junior, has subsided on 
the court, because teammates have begun to take pressure off by shooting 
better. But as Meek has grown into his game -- and closer to college -- 
attention off the court has become so intense that his father, Greg, has 
quarantined him from recruiters until he is senior. 
</P>
<P>
Even so, San Pasqual practices lately have played host to a Who's Who of 
college coaches. 
</P>
<P>
Monday, on the opening day of the week-long NCAA evaluation period, UCLA Coach 
Jim Harrick and Arizona State assistant Lynn Archibald dropped by to make their 
presence known -- even though they had long ago favorably evaluated of Meek. 
</P>
<P>
Others taking a peek at Meek included Arizona's Lute Olson, Arizona State's 
Bill Frieder and Notre Dame's Digger Phelps. 
</P>
<P>
"I can't talk to them, so I just try to go with my day as though they're not 
even there," Meek said. "But it's kind of hard with all those eyes looking at 
you." 
</P>
<P>
Recruiters are also writing Meek an average of 10 letters a day, with 
Vanderbilt, Arizona State and UCLA spending the most money on postage. 
</P>
<P>
The phone also rings quite a bit at the Meek house these days, though all the 
calls are intercepted by Greg. 
</P>
<P>
"We're glad they call, and we appreciate it," Greg Meek said. "But we've set 
down some guidelines. We're not playing any games, and nobody is playing games 
with us." 
</P>
<P>
Except for a few coaches Greg Meek will not identify. He says he did not like 
their initial pitches, and they have been told they would be wasting their time 
recruiting his son. 
</P>
<P>
The elder Meek also said he and his son will not wilt under the pressure of the 
recruiters, meaning he will tell Erik not to commit during the early signing 
period in October if he's not absolutely certain of his choice. 
</P>
<P>
"The only thing the early signing period does is getting the coaches off his 
back," Greg Meek said. "I think it's great for a kid who has grown up in 
Indiana and wanted to play there since sixth grade. But not for kids like 
Erik." 
</P>
<P>
With early signing less than nine months away, it appears Meek is nowhere near 
a decision. He has not even narrowed his choices down to eight or 10 schools 
yet, although he said that time is coming soon. 
</P>
<P>
"It's not fair for all these schools to waste their time and effort if I'm not 
going to go there," Meek said. "So I'm sure after the season, I'll get it down 
to less than 10 schools." 
</P>
<P>
Meek, who has a 3.3 grade-point average, said he will look at a college's 
academics and then its basketball program. Geography doesn't seem to concern 
the Meeks. 
</P>
<P>
"It's education we need to be concerned with," Greg Meek said. "Erik's 
importance to the world is that he's a good person. It's nice that he's a good 
basketball player, too, but we realize if he gets hurt, that could all end in a 
minute." 
</P>
<P>
Greg Meek said his son has handled every situation pretty well so far, 
including an incident last week at a UCLA game when the student body stood up 
and chanted, "We want Meek." 
</P>
<P>
"He doesn't get impressed with it," Greg Meek said. "I told him, 'It's nice, 
but it's programmed.' None of the students knew who Erik was." 
</P>
<P>
But coaches certainly do. Nearly every Division I school has written to him. 
</P>
<P>
Scouting services also know him. 
</P>
<P>
Bob Gibbons of All-Star Sports rates Meek as the second-best junior big man on 
the West Coast. Cherokee Parks of Huntington Beach Marina High, who also rated 
a chant at UCLA, is No. 1. 
</P>
<P>
"Cherokee's a little more advanced offensively, but Erik's a little stronger," 
Gibbons said. "Parks is a little more accomplished all around. But both players 
will be among the top five big men in the United States and top 20 (players) 
overall." 
</P>
<P>
Gibbons said Meek is probably the most heavily recruited player in San Diego 
since Bill Walton was at Helix in 1971. 
</P>
<P>
"He's not Bill Walton, but in his own right, he has to be considered a player 
who will make a major impact on the college level," Gibbons said. 
</P>
<P>
Buck realizes, because Meek is a post player and plays in this area, that 
comparisons to Walton are inevitable. 
</P>
<P>
"But it's not fair to Erik," Buck said. "There's only one Bill Walton, but I 
will say this. Erik's doing things Bill Walton never got the opportunity to 
do." 
</P>
<P>
Such as spending his vacations competing against the top players in the nation 
at the Nike Camp in Princeton, N.J., and driving to Los Angeles to play against 
that area's best in a summer league. 
</P>
<P>
Meek has held his own when he's been matched against the nation's elite 
players, but he realized last summer that his game is still missing some 
ingredients. 
</P>
<P>
"I've seen the best, and I couldn't believe how quick some of these people 
were," Meek said. "I want to get a lot more athletic. By lifting weights and 
working on my quickness, I think I am getting there." 
</P>
<P>
Though his ego has taken a beating on occasion against blue-chip talent, Meek's 
shining moment occured last Easter at a tournament in Las Vegas. While 
competing with his Los Angeles All-Star team, he outplayed 7-5 Shawn Bradley of 
Utah, who has signed with Brigham Young. Meek was later named tournament MVP. 
</P>
<P>
But Bryan Banner, who guards Meek in practice, remembers the days before the 
MVP honors and the letters starting rolling in. 
</P>
<P>
"When I first played with him in seventh grade, he couldn't do much," Banner 
said. "He wasn't very coordinated. He was just big." 
</P>
<P>
Now Meek is big, coordinated and, Banner says, simply unstoppable at times. 
</P>
<P>
"When he drives, it's nearly impossible to stop him," said Banner, who plays 
one-on-one against Meek almost every day after practice. "His jumping ability, 
his balance and his speed have all improved. 
</P>
<P>
Banner said the only thing that ever wavers is Meek's mental game. 
</P>
<P>
"Occasionally, his mind wanders," said Banner, a 6-5 senior. "He doesn't stay 
focused all the time. Sometimes I'll yell at him at halftime and tell him we 
need to start doing more." 
</P>
<P>
Buck said some of the one-on-one battles between the two have been epics. 
</P>
<P>
"When those guys play one-on-one, it's serious," Buck said. "They just beat the 
tar out of each other. Everybody has to clear out of the way when they play." 
</P>
<P>
Banner, who is averaging 16 points this season for ninth-ranked San Pasqual 
(12-5), has given Meek some room to breath during games. 
</P>
<P>
"Bryan has taken a lot of the pressure off me," Meek said. "This year has been 
a lot better for me because of Bryan and some of the other players. Things are 
a lot more spread out for me now." 
</P>
<P>
The balanced San Pasqual attack has allowed Meek, once a one-man gang, to 
branch out and work on other aspects of his game. Meek's shots per game might 
be down this year, but his shooting percentage (68%) and scoring (27.1) are 
both up considerably from last year's 59% and 22.6. His rebounding average has 
stayed at about 11, but that can be attributed to Banner, whose average is up 
to 12 from 7.6. 
</P>
<P>
As a freshman for San Pasqual's 4-18 team, Meek averaged 19.8 points and once 
scored 38 against Mt. Carmel's Shane Knight, who is headed for BYU next year. 
</P>
<P>
"He just did some things very well as a freshman," said Ramona Coach Al 
Schaffer before Meek scored 25 points against his Bulldogs Wednesday night in a 
73-45 San Pasqual victory. "But now he's running the floor better, and he seems 
to have improved his all-around game. The thing I like about him is if he makes 
a mistake, he doesn't let it bother him." 
</P>
<P>
Not much seems to bother Meek, including pesky recruiters and five-on-one 
defenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Even though improved teammates have given defenses something else to 
worry about, Erik Meek still gets a lot of attention; he is one of the 
country's top junior big men, averaging 27.1 points, 11 rebounds a game. ; 
Photo, Out-of-towners such as Brad Holland, a UCLA assistant, have been hanging 
around San Pasqual, but Meek can't talk to any of them. DAVE GATLEY / Los 
Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
