<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: COURT DENIES APPEAL OF BRUTALITY RULING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 9th Circuit Court of Appeals has denied an appeal by the city of Glendale, 
letting stand an earlier federal court verdict awarding a Canoga Park man 
$60,000 in a police brutality case. 
</P>
<P>
The case involved Paul Valles, who brought action against the city, several 
police officers and jailers. 
</P>
<P>
Valles alleged that in November, 1986, Glendale police officers arrested him 
illegally, used excessive force and were indifferent to his medical needs in a 
one-night stay in jail. 
</P>
<P>
During the trial in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles, the officers contended 
that Valles had been drunk in a public place and resisted arrest. They tried to 
introduce as evidence Valles' prior lawsuit against the Los Angeles Police 
Department and statements he made during a previous arrest as proof that he was 
biased against police in general. 
</P>
<P>
The judge excluded this evidence, and the jury ruled in Valles' favor. The 
decision, filed Tuesday, also awards the legal firm representing the plaintiff 
$71,000 in attorney fees, said Valles' lawyer, Stephen Yagman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
