</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: LAGUNA BEACH; 
</P>
<P>
CONTROLLED BLAZE JUMPS FIRE LINES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A controlled fire Thursday in Emerald Canyon jumped fire lines and blackened an 
area that was scheduled to be burned today. 
</P>
<P>
"Dryness of the soil and the severe fire hazard, as well as a little wind, 
caused the fire to jump over lines we had set for (Thursday's) burn," Orange 
County Fire Department Capt. Hank Raymond said. 
</P>
<P>
The wind-whipped fire burned about 50 acres more than was scheduled for 
Thursday's operation. "But the area . . . is still well within the total 
500-acre controlled burn site," Raymond said. 
</P>
<P>
Fire officials summoned 10 more fire engines to the scene -- a contingency plan 
that is implemented when flames jump fire lines, Raymond said. 
</P>
<P>
Smoke from the fire was visible over a wide area of the South County, Raymond 
said, prompting many calls to the Fire Department. 
</P>
<P>
Raymond said the major part of the controlled burned will take place today if 
the weather and the winds permit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
