</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Bush "opposes segregation in any form" but plans to attend social 
functions hosted by two all-male clubs in Washington on Saturday, his spokesman 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
As he did last year, the President will attend a luncheon sponsored by the 
Alibi Club, which meets on regular occasions, and the annual dinner of the 
Alfalfa Club, which meets once a year to roast political personalities. 
</P>
<P>
White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush is attending the two 
functions "for the same reason he did last year -- because he belongs to both 
clubs and enjoys them." 
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the President should attend a segregated gathering, 
Fitzwater said, "I don't think it's relevant" and added, "The President is 
opposed to segregation in any form." 
</P>
