</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
OZONE FOES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Clipboard researched by Elena Brunet and Janice L. Jones / Los Angeles 
Times; Graphics by Scott Brown and Doris Shields / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a report recently released by the environmental group Natural Resources 
Defense Council, 56 county firms were listed among the top 3,014 companies in 
the nation using three chemicals known to deplete the Earth's ozone layer. The 
companies were ranked on a weighted basis according to how much of each of the 
three chemicals -- methyl chloroform, carbon tetrachloride and a 
chlorofluorocarbon known as CFC-113 -- they use. The report was based on 
federal government figures derived from the companies' own reports under the 
federal "right to know" law. Companies were required to begin reporting the 
information in 1987, and, in most instances, those are the most recent numbers 
available. Below is a list of how all the county companies ranked and the 
thousands of pounds of the chemicals in question for the years 1987 and, in 
some cases, 1988. The higher the ranking, the more dangerous the company's 
emissions, according to NRDC. There are no numbers available for carbon 
tetrachloride for either year. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
